content: Shields Library's restrooms are a scholar's haven. Spotless and private, though the hand dryers lack power. A near-perfect study break stop.
Memorial Union's restrooms manage the crowd decently. Accessibility is solid, but the overused air freshener scent detracts. Just average.
Mrak Hall's restrooms are pristine and spacious. A calming retreat in an admin building. Simply flawless.
Wellman Hall's restrooms feel chaotic from constant use. They’re functional but lack privacy and fresh air. Disappointing.
Olson Hall's restrooms charm with their cleanliness. Queues during class changes are the only flaw. A solid pick.
The ARC's restrooms are gym-appropriate but loud. Eco-friendly fixtures shine, yet the bustle overwhelms. Fair enough.
Student Community Center's restrooms are a masterpiece. Inclusive, spacious, and spotless. Campus perfection.
Teaching Learning Complex's restrooms impress with modern design. Private and serene, though dryers lag. Nearly ideal.
Earth and Physical Sciences' restrooms try hard with eco-tech. Flushless urinals confuse, and cleanliness varies. Decent effort.
Giedt Hall's restrooms blend style and function. Clean and modern, but peak-hour waits disrupt the vibe. Still great.
Bainer Hall's restrooms are a letdown. Dingy and cramped, they scream neglect. Barely passable.
Activities and Recreation Center's restrooms dazzle. Sleek, clean, and refreshing after a workout. Top-tier.
Kemper Hall's restrooms are practical but uninspired. Clean enough, yet the lighting feels harsh. Middle ground.
Social Sciences and Humanities' restrooms shine quietly. Spacious and tidy, though soap dispensers often run low. Very good.

Hutchison Hall's restrooms get the job done. They’re average in cleanliness, with dated fixtures. Nothing special.
